Sweet Pea & Friends
April 6 at 9:10 AM ¬∑

[Author StoryTime] You're Invited EASTER SUNDAY
Gather up the kids and their favorite Sweet Pea & Friends books and join us online Easter Sunday starting at 10am for an "Easter Surprise".
By special permission from our publisher, Little Brown Books for Young Readers, we'll be releasing a full length reading of our book THE EASTER SURPRISE with the storybook pictures! It will be available for you to watch all day and we'll be answering reader questions and posting special Sweet Pea & Friends farm life pictures/videos in the comments throughout the day.
Happy Easter from our home to yours! ~ John and Jen Churchman

Read along with your own copy and support your Independent Booksellers offering "curbside books" or the Sweet Pea & Friends Farm Store if you want a signed/personalized copy sent to you

Indie Bookstores: www.org/indie-bookstore-finder

Sweet Pea & Friends Farm Store:
www.sweetpeafriendsbookstore.com

Amazon:
www.amazon.com/Easter-Surprise-Sweet-Pea-Friends/dp/0316411663/ref=sr_1_2?dchild=1&keywords=the+easter+surprise&qid=1586137937&sr=8-2

post_text:
To our Loyal Patrons,

In response to the developing COVID-19 situation, Chazy Public Library will be closed effective immediately. During this suspension of normal activity we will attempt to provide you with some limited services to the best of our ability. Our wifi network will be freely accessible from our parking lot. On select hours, we will offer a rotating collection of free books on a cart outside our entrance. We also anticipate being able to fill custom requests ‚Äì placed by phone, email, though our online catalog, or FB messenger ‚Äì for books and videos from our collection which will also be provided outside our entrance for pickup during select hours. More details on that process will be announced soon.

All the best everyone,

Blake Andrew
Director

New York Public Library honors its most borrowed book for 125th anniversary

ABC World News Tonight with David Muir
January 13 at 7:30 PM ¬∑

There are millions of books to choose from at the New York Public Library, but in the system's 125-year history, a simple illustrated children's story has stood the test of time and transcended generations as the most-borrowed book.

The library announced "The Snowy Day" by Ezra Jack Keats, which tells the tale of Peter and his wintry adventure, has tallied the most checkouts with 485,583.
